<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: Outside of home areas...</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?Stupid">Stupid</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 4:05 a.m. 14/5/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: Outside of home areas...<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=2048" TARGET=_self>Outside of home areas...</A> (Malark)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>> Is there a

<BR>&gt; mostly an unspoken peace with people eyeing each oher warily and
<BR>&gt; staying out of the way? Or do bands of vigilantes roam the areas
<BR>&gt; killing anyone they see (I know its not THAT bad, I'm just using
<BR>&gt; an extreme).
<P>It pretty much depends on the situation. As a Troll, when I'm in the Commonlands or even Ro, when I see a "good" race, I imediately go into self-preservation mode. Unless I have a clear-cut advantage, I wont attack. There are just too many unknowns. The guy might be grouped with seventeen other people just over the next hill. Besides, I suspect people are going to use my own tactics against me.
<P>On the other hand, if I see a human, gnome, or wood elf in the swamp, feerrott or in Guk, it is "scream and leap" time. I usually wont even bother con'ing them. Just blindly attack! If I win, then I've "saved" my Troll brothers from an invader. If I lose, then I rally other with the battle cry of how I was killed by the interloper (which is true -- I just omit the part about how I attacked them first...). Either way, I win.
<P>&gt; What about places like Befallen, Crushbone,
<BR>&gt; Cazic-Thule, and Guk? Is there an uneasy truce between bands of
<BR>&gt; adventurers who know how easy it is for a fight to turn into a
<BR>&gt; pellmell run to the exit? How hard is it to get higher of level
<BR>&gt; when most of the bigger monsters are in relatively neutral
<BR>&gt; areas?
<P>In my experience, the dungeon areas are "owned" by whomever lives closest to them. Wary eyeballs are the order of the day, but violins can erupt without warning. If one group takes a beating, the second group may or may not take advantage of the situation. Again, it is very situational. In a game where death has a bite, most are not really willing to jump into a combat that they might lose.
<P>&gt; Malark, currently on Karana
<P>Come join us on Rallos. It's a lot more fun than the CareBear servers.
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
